Health Ombudsman Professor Malegapuru Makgoba revealed that 94 psychiatric patients died after being transferred to 27 NGOs. JOHANNESBURG - The Gauteng provincial government says the moving of the patients from the five high risk NGOs that have been identified in the Health Ombudsman's report into the Life Healthcare Esidimeni tragedy is now being treated as a priority.Last week, Professor Malegapuru Makgoba revealed that 94 psychiatric patients died after being transferred to 27 NGOs which were not licensed to take care of the mentally-ill.Former Health MEC Qedani Mahlangu resigned just hours before the report was due to be released.On Monday, Mahlangu s successor Dr Gwen Ramokgopa was sworn in as a member of the Gauteng Legislature and as the new MEC.The provincial government s Phumla Sekhonyane says the moving of patients under the Gauteng mental health marathon project has now been stopped. We are prioritising patients that are still at the NGOs. The first recommendation was that the project must be stopped and it has been stopped. The Gauteng government says disciplinary proceedings against other officials in the health department, including the HOD and director began last Friday.Three of the biggest hospitals in the province have been placed on high alert to deal with emergencies or critical cases that may arise from the NGOs.Christa Eybers | A timeline of the events leading up to deaths of 94 psychiatric patients from Life Esidimeni, and the subsequent investigations.(Edited by Winnie Theletsane)